[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] The form $\alpha \rightarrow \varepsilon$ is called an ε-production.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] It is common to list all right-hand sides for the same left-hand side on the same line, using | (the vertical bar) to separate them.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Rules $\alpha \rightarrow \beta _{1}$ and $\alpha \rightarrow \beta _{2}$ can hence be written as $\alpha \rightarrow \beta _{1}\mid \beta _{2}$ .
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] In this case, $\beta _{1}$ and $\beta _{2}$ are called the first and second alternative, respectively.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Thus, v is a result of applying the rule $(\alpha ,\beta )$ to *u*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] For any strings $u,v\in (V\cup \Sigma )^{*},$ we say u *yields* v or v is *derived* from u if there is a positive integer k and strings $u_{1},\ldots ,u_{k}\in (V\cup \Sigma )^{*}$ such that $u=u_{1}\Rightarrow u_{2}\Rightarrow \cdots \Rightarrow u_{k}=v$ .
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] This relation is denoted $u~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~v$ , or $u\Rightarrow \Rightarrow v$ in some textbooks.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] If $k\geq 2$ , the relation $u~{\stackrel {+}{\Rightarrow }}~v$ holds.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] In other words, $({\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }})$ and $({\stackrel {+}{\Rightarrow }})$ are the reflexive transitive closure (allowing a string to yield itself) and the transitive closure (requiring at least one step) of $(\Rightarrow )$ , respectively.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] of all terminal-symbol strings derivable from the start symbol.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] A language L is said to be a context-free language (CFL), if there exists a CFG G, such that $L=L(G)$ .
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Non-deterministic pushdown automata recognize exactly the context-free languages.
