[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] The language described is all nonempty strings of as and bs that end in a.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] This grammar is regular: no rule has more than one nonterminal in its right-hand side, and each of these nonterminals is at the same end of the right-hand side.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Every regular grammar corresponds directly to a nondeterministic finite automaton, so we know that this is a regular language.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] A *derivation* of a string for a grammar is a sequence of grammar rule applications that transform the start symbol into the string.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] A derivation proves that the string belongs to the grammar's language.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] For clarity, the intermediate string is usually given as well.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Given such a strategy, a derivation is completely determined by the sequence of rules applied.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] The distinction between leftmost derivation and rightmost derivation is important because in most parsers the transformation of the input is defined by giving a piece of code for every grammar rule that is executed whenever the rule is applied.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Therefore, it is important to know whether the parser determines a leftmost or a rightmost derivation because this determines the order in which the pieces of code will be executed.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] See for an example LL parsers and LR parsers.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] A derivation also imposes in some sense a hierarchical structure on the string that is derived.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] where {...}*S* denotes a substring recognized as belonging to *S*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] This tree is called a *parse tree* or "concrete syntax tree" of the string, by contrast with the abstract syntax tree.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Note however that both parse trees can be obtained by both leftmost and rightmost derivations.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] If a string in the language of the grammar has more than one parsing tree, then the grammar is said to be an *ambiguous grammar*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Such grammars are usually hard to parse because the parser cannot always decide which grammar rule it has to apply.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Usually, ambiguity is a feature of the grammar, not the language, and an unambiguous grammar can be found that generates the same context-free language.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] However, there are certain languages that can only be generated by ambiguous grammars; such languages are called *inherently ambiguous languages*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Every context-free grammar with no ε-production has an equivalent grammar in Chomsky normal form, and a grammar in Greibach normal form.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] "Equivalent" here means that the two grammars generate the same language.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] The especially simple form of production rules in Chomsky normal form grammars has both theoretical and practical implications.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] For instance, given a context-free grammar, one can use the Chomsky normal form to construct a polynomial-time algorithm that decides whether a given string is in the language represented by that grammar or not (the CYK algorithm).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] They are not closed under general intersection (hence neither under complementation) and set difference.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] The following are some decidable problems about context-free grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Context-free parsing for Chomsky normal form grammars was shown by Leslie G.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Valiant to be reducible to Boolean matrix multiplication, thus inheriting its complexity upper bound of *O*(*n*2.3728639).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Conversely, Lillian Lee has shown *O*(*n*3−*ε*) Boolean matrix multiplication to be reducible to *O*(*n*3−3*ε*) CFG parsing, thus establishing some kind of lower bound for the latter.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] A nonterminal symbol X is called *productive*, or *generating*, if there is a derivation $X~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~w$ for some string w of terminal symbols.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] X is called *reachable* if there is a derivation $S~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~\alpha X\beta$ for some strings $\alpha ,\beta$ of nonterminal and terminal symbols from the start symbol.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] X is called *useless* if it is unreachable or unproductive.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] X is called *nullable* if there is a derivation $X~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~\varepsilon$ .
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] A rule $X\rightarrow \varepsilon$ is called an *ε-production*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] A derivation $X~{\stackrel {+}{\Rightarrow }}~X$ is called a *cycle*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] In particular, an alternative containing a useless nonterminal symbol can be deleted from the right-hand side of a rule.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Such rules and alternatives are called *useless*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] In the depicted example grammar, the nonterminal *D* is unreachable, and *E* is unproductive, while *C* → *C* causes a cycle.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Hence, omitting the last three rules does not change the language generated by the grammar, nor does omitting the alternatives "| *C*c | *E*e" from the right-hand side of the rule for *S*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] A context-free grammar is said to be *proper* if it has neither useless symbols nor ε-productions nor cycles.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Combining the above algorithms, every context-free grammar not generating ε can be transformed into a weakly equivalent proper one.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] It is decidable whether a given *grammar* is a regular grammar, as well as whether it is an LL(*k*) grammar for a given *k* ≥ 0.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] If *k* is not given, the latter problem is undecidable.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Given a context-free grammar, it is not decidable whether its language is regular, nor whether it is an LL(*k*) language for a given *k*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] There are algorithms to decide whether the language of a given context-free grammar is empty, as well as whether it is finite.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Some questions that are undecidable for wider classes of grammars become decidable for context-free grammars; e.g. the emptiness problem (whether the grammar generates any terminal strings at all), is undecidable for context-sensitive grammars, but decidable for context-free grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] However, many problems are undecidable even for context-free grammars; the most prominent ones are handled in the following.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Given a CFG, does it generate the language of all strings over the alphabet of terminal symbols used in its rules?
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] A reduction can be demonstrated to this problem from the well-known undecidable problem of determining whether a Turing machine accepts a particular input (the halting problem).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] The reduction uses the concept of a *computation history*, a string describing an entire computation of a Turing machine.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] A CFG can be constructed that generates all strings that are not accepting computation histories for a particular Turing machine on a particular input, and thus it will accept all strings only if the machine does not accept that input.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, do they generate the same language?
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] The undecidability of this problem is a direct consequence of the previous: it is impossible to even decide whether a CFG is equivalent to the trivial CFG defining the language of all strings.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, can the first one generate all strings that the second one can generate?
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] If this problem was decidable, then language equality could be decided too: two CFGs $G_{1}$ and $G_{2}$ generate the same language if $L(G_{1})$ is a subset of $L(G_{2})$ and $L(G_{2})$ is a subset of $L(G_{1})$ .
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] The undecidability of this problem follows from the fact that if an algorithm to determine ambiguity existed, the Post correspondence problem could be decided, which is known to be undecidable.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, is there any string derivable from both grammars?
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Then the PCP instance given by $\alpha _{1},\ldots ,\alpha _{N},\beta _{1},\ldots ,\beta _{N}$ has a solution if and only if ⁠ $L(G_{1})$ ⁠ and ⁠ $L(G_{2})$ ⁠ share a derivable string.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] The left of the string (before the b ) will represent the top of the solution for the PCP instance while the right side will be the bottom in reverse.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] An obvious way to extend the context-free grammar formalism is to allow nonterminals to have arguments, the values of which are passed along within the rules.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] This allows natural language features such as agreement and reference, and programming language analogs such as the correct use and definition of identifiers, to be expressed in a natural way.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] E.g. we can now easily express that in English sentences, the subject and verb must agree in number.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] In computer science, examples of this approach include affix grammars, attribute grammars, indexed grammars, and Van Wijngaarden two-level grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Similar extensions exist in linguistics.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] An **extended context-free grammar** (or **regular right part grammar**) is one in which the right-hand side of the production rules is allowed to be a regular expression over the grammar's terminals and nonterminals.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Extended context-free grammars describe exactly the context-free languages.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Another extension is to allow additional terminal symbols to appear at the left-hand side of rules, constraining their application.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] This produces the formalism of context-sensitive grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] LR parsing extends LL parsing to support a larger range of grammars; in turn, generalized LR parsing extends LR parsing to support arbitrary context-free grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] On LL grammars and LR grammars, it essentially performs LL parsing and LR parsing, respectively, while on nondeterministic grammars, it is as efficient as can be expected.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Although GLR parsing was developed in the 1980s, many new language definitions and parser generators continue to be based on LL, LALR or LR parsing up to the present day.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Chomsky initially hoped to overcome the limitations of context-free grammars by adding transformation rules.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Such rules are another standard device in traditional linguistics; e.g. passivization in English.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Much of generative grammar has been devoted to finding ways of refining the descriptive mechanisms of phrase-structure grammar and transformation rules such that exactly the kinds of things can be expressed that natural language actually allows.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Allowing arbitrary transformations does not meet that goal: they are much too powerful, being Turing complete unless significant restrictions are added (e.g. no transformations that introduce and then rewrite symbols in a context-free fashion).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Chomsky's general position regarding the non-context-freeness of natural language has held up since then, although his specific examples regarding the inadequacy of context-free grammars in terms of their weak generative capacity were later disproved.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/context-free-grammar] Gerald Gazdar and Geoffrey Pullum have argued that despite a few non-context-free constructions in natural language (such as cross-serial dependencies in Swiss German and reduplication in Bambara), the vast majority of forms in natural language are indeed context-free.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The notion of dependencies between grammatical units has existed since the earliest recorded grammars, e.g.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Pāṇini, and the dependency concept therefore arguably predates that of phrase structure by many centuries.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Ibn Maḍāʾ, a 12th-century linguist from Córdoba, Andalusia, may have been the first grammarian to use the term *dependency* in the grammatical sense that we use it today.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] In early modern times, the dependency concept seems to have coexisted side by side with that of phrase structure, the latter having entered Latin, French, English and other grammars from the widespread study of term logic of antiquity.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency is also concretely present in the works of Sámuel Brassai (1800–1897), a Hungarian linguist, Franz Kern (1830–1894), a German philologist, and of Heimann Hariton Tiktin (1850–1936), a Romanian linguist.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Modern dependency grammars, however, begin primarily with the work of Lucien Tesnière.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Tesnière was a Frenchman, a polyglot, and a professor of linguistics at the universities in Strasbourg and Montpellier.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] His major work *Éléments de syntaxe structurale* was published posthumously in 1959 – he died in 1954.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The basic approach to syntax he developed has at least partially influenced the work of others in the 1960s, although it is not clear in what way these works were inspired by other sources.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] A number of other dependency-based grammars have gained prominence since those early works.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] DG has generated a lot of interest in Germany in both theoretical syntax and language pedagogy.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] In recent years, the great development surrounding dependency-based theories has come from computational linguistics and is due, in part, to the influential work that David Hays did in machine translation at the RAND Corporation in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency-based systems are increasingly being used to parse natural language and generate tree banks.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Interest in dependency grammar is growing at present, international conferences on dependency linguistics being a relatively recent development (Depling 2011, Depling 2013, Depling 2015, Depling 2017, Depling 2019 Archived 2019-03-06 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency is a one-to-one correspondence: for every element (e.g. word or morph) in the sentence, there is exactly one node in the structure of that sentence that corresponds to that element.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The result of this one-to-one correspondence is that dependency grammars are word (or morph) grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] All that exist are the elements and the dependencies that connect the elements into a structure.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] This situation should be compared with phrase structure.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Phrase structure is a one-to-one-or-more correspondence, which means that, for every element in a sentence, there are one or more nodes in the structure that correspond to that element.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The result of this difference is that dependency structures are minimal compared to their phrase structure counterparts, since they tend to contain many fewer nodes.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] These trees illustrate two possible ways to render the dependency and phrase structure relations (see below).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] This dependency tree is an "ordered" tree, i.e. it reflects actual word order.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Many dependency trees abstract away from linear order and focus just on hierarchical order, which means they do not show actual word order.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] This constituency (= phrase structure) tree follows the conventions of bare phrase structure (BPS), whereby the words themselves are employed as the node labels.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The distinction between dependency and phrase structure grammars derives in large part from the initial division of the clause.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The phrase structure relation derives from an initial binary division, whereby the clause is split into a subject noun phrase (NP) and a predicate verb phrase (VP).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] This division is certainly present in the basic analysis of the clause that we find in the works of, for instance, Leonard Bloomfield and Noam Chomsky.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Tesnière, however, argued vehemently against this binary division, preferring instead to position the verb as the root of all clause structure.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Tesnière's stance was that the subject-predicate division stems from term logic and has no place in linguistics.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Link grammar is similar to dependency grammar, but link grammar does not include directionality between the linked words, and thus does not describe head-dependent relationships.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Hybrid dependency/phrase structure grammar uses dependencies between words, but also includes dependencies between phrasal nodes – see for example the Quranic Arabic Dependency Treebank.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The derivation trees of tree-adjoining grammar are dependency structures, although the full trees of TAG rendered in terms of phrase structure, so in this regard, it is not clear whether TAG should be viewed more as a dependency or phrase structure grammar.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] There are major differences between the grammars just listed.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] In this regard, the dependency relation is compatible with other major tenets of theories of grammar.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Thus like phrase structure grammars, dependency grammars can be mono- or multistratal, representational or derivational, construction- or rule-based.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] There are various conventions that DGs employ to represent dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The representations in (a–d) are trees, whereby the specific conventions employed in each tree vary.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Solid lines are *dependency edges* and lightly dotted lines are *projection lines*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The only difference between tree (a) and tree (b) is that tree (a) employs the category class to label the nodes whereas tree (b) employs the words themselves as the node labels.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Tree (c) is a reduced tree insofar as the string of words below and projection lines are deemed unnecessary and are hence omitted.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Tree (d) abstracts away from linear order and reflects just hierarchical order.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The arrow arcs in (e) are an alternative convention used to show dependencies and are favored by Word Grammar.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The brackets in (f) are seldom used, but are nevertheless quite capable of reflecting the dependency hierarchy; dependents appear enclosed in more brackets than their heads.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] And finally, the indentations like those in (g) are another convention that is sometimes employed to indicate the hierarchy of words.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependents are placed underneath their heads and indented.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Like tree (d), the indentations in (g) abstract away from linear order.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The point to these conventions is that they are just that, namely conventions.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] They do not influence the basic commitment to dependency as the relation that is grouping syntactic units.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The dependency representations above (and further below) show syntactic dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Indeed, most work in dependency grammar focuses on syntactic dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Syntactic dependencies are, however, just one of three or four types of dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Meaning–text theory, for instance, emphasizes the role of semantic and morphological dependencies in addition to syntactic dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] A fourth type, prosodic dependencies, can also be acknowledged.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Distinguishing between these types of dependencies can be important, in part because if one fails to do so, the likelihood that semantic, morphological, and/or prosodic dependencies will be mistaken for syntactic dependencies is great.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The following four subsections briefly sketch each of these dependency types.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] During the discussion, the existence of syntactic dependencies is taken for granted and used as an orientation point for establishing the nature of the other three dependency types.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Semantic dependencies are understood in terms of predicates and their arguments.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The arguments of a predicate are semantically dependent on that predicate.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Often, semantic dependencies overlap with and point in the same direction as syntactic dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] At times, however, semantic dependencies can point in the opposite direction of syntactic dependencies, or they can be entirely independent of syntactic dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The two arguments *Sam* and *Sally* in tree (a) are dependent on the predicate *likes*, whereby these arguments are also syntactically dependent on *likes*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] What this means is that the semantic and syntactic dependencies overlap and point in the same direction (down the tree).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Attributive adjectives, however, are predicates that take their head noun as their argument, hence *big* is a predicate in tree (b) that takes *bones* as its one argument; the semantic dependency points up the tree and therefore runs counter to the syntactic dependency.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] A similar situation obtains in (c), where the preposition predicate *on* takes the two arguments *the picture* and *the wall*; one of these semantic dependencies points up the syntactic hierarchy, whereas the other points down it.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Finally, the predicate *to help* in (d) takes the one argument *Jim* but is not directly connected to *Jim* in the syntactic hierarchy, which means that semantic dependency is entirely independent of the syntactic dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Morphological dependencies obtain between words or parts of words.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] When a given word or part of a word influences the form of another word, then the latter is morphologically dependent on the former.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Agreement and concord are therefore manifestations of morphological dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Like semantic dependencies, morphological dependencies can overlap with and point in the same direction as syntactic dependencies, overlap with and point in the opposite direction of syntactic dependencies, or be entirely independent of syntactic dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The arrows are now used to indicate morphological dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The plural *houses* in (a) demands the plural of the demonstrative determiner, hence *these* appears, not *this*, which means there is a morphological dependency that points down the hierarchy from *houses* to *these*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The situation is reversed in (b), where the singular subject *Sam* demands the appearance of the agreement suffix *-s* on the finite verb *works*, which means there is a morphological dependency pointing up the hierarchy from *Sam* to *works*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The type of determiner in the German examples (c) and (d) influences the inflectional suffix that appears on the adjective *alt*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] When the indefinite article *ein* is used, the strong masculine ending *-er* appears on the adjective.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] When the definite article *der* is used, in contrast, the weak ending *-e* appears on the adjective.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Thus since the choice of determiner impacts the morphological form of the adjective, there is a morphological dependency pointing from the determiner to the adjective, whereby this morphological dependency is entirely independent of the syntactic dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The masculine subject *le chien* in (a) demands the masculine form of the predicative adjective *blanc*, whereas the feminine subject *la maison* demands the feminine form of this adjective.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] A morphological dependency that is entirely independent of the syntactic dependencies therefore points again across the syntactic hierarchy.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Morphological dependencies play an important role in typological studies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Languages are classified as mostly head-marking (*Sam work-s*) or mostly dependent-marking (*these houses*), whereby most if not all languages contain at least some minor measure of both head and dependent marking.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Prosodic dependencies are acknowledged in order to accommodate the behavior of clitics.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] A clitic is a syntactically autonomous element that is prosodically dependent on a host.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] A clitic is therefore integrated into the prosody of its host, meaning that it forms a single word with its host.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Prosodic dependencies exist entirely in the linear dimension (horizontal dimension), whereas standard syntactic dependencies exist in the hierarchical dimension (vertical dimension).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Classic examples of clitics in English are reduced auxiliaries (e.g.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] A given clitic is often prosodically dependent on its syntactic dependent (*He'll*, *There's*) or on its head (*would've*).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] At other times, it can depend prosodically on a word that is neither its head nor its immediate dependent (*Florida's*).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Syntactic dependencies are the focus of most work in DG, as stated above.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] How the presence and the direction of syntactic dependencies are determined is of course often open to debate.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] In this regard, it must be acknowledged that the validity of syntactic dependencies in the trees throughout this article is being taken for granted.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] However, these hierarchies are such that many DGs can largely support them, although there will certainly be points of disagreement.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The basic question about how syntactic dependencies are discerned has proven difficult to answer definitively.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] One should acknowledge in this area, however, that the basic task of identifying and discerning the presence and direction of the syntactic dependencies of DGs is no easier or harder than determining the constituent groupings of phrase structure grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Etymological considerations also provide helpful clues about the direction of dependencies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] A promising principle upon which to base the existence of syntactic dependencies is distribution.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] When one is striving to identify the root of a given phrase, the word that is most responsible for determining the distribution of that phrase as a whole is its root.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Traditionally, DGs have had a different approach to linear order (word order) than phrase structure grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency structures are minimal compared to their phrase structure counterparts, and these minimal structures allow one to focus intently on the two ordering dimensions.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Separating the vertical dimension (hierarchical order) from the horizontal dimension (linear order) is easily accomplished.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] This aspect of dependency structures has allowed DGs, starting with Tesnière (1959), to focus on hierarchical order in a manner that is hardly possible for phrase structure grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] For Tesnière, linear order was secondary to hierarchical order insofar as hierarchical order preceded linear order in the mind of a speaker.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The stemmas (trees) that Tesnière produced reflected this view; they abstracted away from linear order to focus almost entirely on hierarchical order.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Many DGs that followed Tesnière adopted this practice, that is, they produced tree structures that reflect hierarchical order alone, e.g.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The traditional focus on hierarchical order generated the impression that DGs have little to say about linear order, and it has contributed to the view that DGs are particularly well-suited to examine languages with free word order.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] A negative result of this focus on hierarchical order, however, is that there is a dearth of DG explorations of particular word order phenomena, such as of standard discontinuities.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Comprehensive dependency grammar accounts of topicalization, *wh*-fronting, scrambling, and extraposition are mostly absent from many established DG frameworks.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] This situation can be contrasted with phrase structure grammars, which have devoted tremendous effort to exploring these phenomena.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The nature of the dependency relation does not, however, prevent one from focusing on linear order.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency structures are as capable of exploring word order phenomena as phrase structures.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The following trees illustrate this point; they represent one way of exploring discontinuities using dependency structures.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The trees suggest the manner in which common discontinuities can be addressed.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The a-trees on the left show projectivity violations (= crossing lines), and the b-trees on the right demonstrate one means of addressing these violations.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The displaced constituent takes on a word as its head that is not its governor.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The words in red mark the catena (=chain) of words that extends from the root of the displaced constituent to the governor of that constituent.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Discontinuities are then explored in terms of these catenae.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The limitations on topicalization, *wh*-fronting, scrambling, and extraposition can be explored and identified by examining the nature of the catenae involved.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Traditionally, DGs have treated the syntactic functions (= grammatical functions, grammatical relations) as primitive.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] They posit an inventory of functions (e.g. subject, object, oblique, determiner, attribute, predicative, etc.).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] These functions can appear as labels on the dependencies in the tree structures, e.g.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The syntactic functions in this tree are shown in green: ATTR (attribute), COMP-P (complement of preposition), COMP-TO (complement of to), DET (determiner), P-ATTR (prepositional attribute), PRED (predicative), SUBJ (subject), TO-COMP (to complement).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The functions chosen and abbreviations used in the tree here are merely representative of the general stance of DGs toward the syntactic functions.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The actual inventory of functions and designations employed vary from DG to DG.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] As a primitive of the theory, the status of these functions is very different from that in some phrase structure grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Traditionally, phrase structure grammars derive the syntactic functions from the constellation.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] For instance, the object is identified as the NP appearing inside finite VP, and the subject as the NP appearing outside of finite VP.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Since DGs reject the existence of a finite VP constituent, they were never presented with the option to view the syntactic functions in this manner.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] This question about what comes first (the functions or the constellation) is not an inflexible matter.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] The stances of both grammar types (dependency and phrase structure) are not narrowly limited to the traditional views.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency and phrase structure are both fully compatible with both approaches to the syntactic functions.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] Indeed, monostratal systems, that are solely based on dependency or phrase structure, will likely reject the notion that the functions are derived from the constellation or that the constellation is derived from the functions.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/dependency-grammar] They will take both to be primitive, which means neither can be derived from the other.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] A rule-based program, performing lexical tokenization, is called *tokenizer*, or *scanner*, although *scanner* is also a term for the first stage of a lexer.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] A lexer forms the first phase of a compiler frontend in processing.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexers and parsers are most often used for compilers, but can be used for other computer language tools, such as prettyprinters or linters.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexing can be divided into two stages: the *scanning*, which segments the input string into syntactic units called *lexemes* and categorizes these into token classes, and the *evaluating*, which converts lexemes into processed values.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexers are generally quite simple, with most of the complexity deferred to the syntactic analysis or semantic analysis phases, and can often be generated by a lexer generator, notably lex or derivatives.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] However, lexers can sometimes include some complexity, such as phrase structure processing to make input easier and simplify the parser, and may be written partly or fully by hand, either to support more features or for performance.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing is not equal to what is called lexeme in linguistics.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing can be equal to the linguistic equivalent only in analytic languages, such as English, but not in highly synthetic languages, such as fusional languages.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] What is called a lexeme in rule-based natural language processing is more similar to what is called a word in linguistics (not to be confused with a word in computer architecture), although in some cases it may be more similar to a morpheme.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] A *lexical token* is a string with an assigned and thus identified meaning, in contrast to the probabilistic token used in large language models.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] A lexical token consists of a *token name* and an optional *token value*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The token name is a category of a rule-based lexical unit.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] A token name is what might be termed a part of speech in linguistics.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] the string is not implicitly segmented on spaces, as a natural language speaker would do.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The raw input, the 43 characters, must be explicitly split into the 9 tokens with a given space delimiter (i.e., matching the string `" "` or regular expression `/\s{1}/`).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] When a token class represents more than one possible lexeme, the lexer often saves enough information to reproduce the original lexeme, so that it can be used in semantic analysis.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The parser typically retrieves this information from the lexer and stores it in the abstract syntax tree.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] This is necessary in order to avoid information loss in the case where numbers may also be valid identifiers.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Tokens are identified based on the specific rules of the lexer.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Some methods used to identify tokens include regular expressions, specific sequences of characters termed a flag, specific separating characters called delimiters, and explicit definition by a dictionary.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Special characters, including punctuation characters, are commonly used by lexers to identify tokens because of their natural use in written and programming languages.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] A lexical analyzer generally does nothing with combinations of tokens, a task left for a parser.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] For example, a typical lexical analyzer recognizes parentheses as tokens but does nothing to ensure that each "(" is matched with a ")".
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] When a lexer feeds tokens to the parser, the representation used is typically an enumerated type, which is a list of number representations.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] For example, "Identifier" can be represented with 0, "Assignment operator" with 1, "Addition operator" with 2, etc.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Tokens are often defined by regular expressions, which are understood by a lexical analyzer generator such as lex, or handcoded equivalent finite-state automata.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The lexical analyzer (generated automatically by a tool like lex or hand-crafted) reads in a stream of characters, identifies the lexemes in the stream, and categorizes them into tokens.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] If the lexer finds an invalid token, it will report an error.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] From there, the interpreted data may be loaded into data structures for general use, interpretation, or compiling.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The specification of a programming language often includes a set of rules, the lexical grammar, which defines the lexical syntax.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The lexical syntax is usually a regular language, with the grammar rules consisting of regular expressions; they define the set of possible character sequences (lexemes) of a token.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] A lexer recognizes strings, and for each kind of string found, the lexical program takes an action, most simply producing a token.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Two important common lexical categories are white space and comments.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] These are also defined in the grammar and processed by the lexer but may be discarded (not producing any tokens) and considered *non-significant*, at most separating two tokens (as in `if x` instead of `ifx`).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] There are two important exceptions to this.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] First, in off-side rule languages that delimit blocks with indenting, initial whitespace is significant, as it determines block structure, and is generally handled at the lexer level; see phrase structure, below.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Secondly, in some uses of lexers, comments and whitespace must be preserved – for examples, a prettyprinter also needs to output the comments and some debugging tools may provide messages to the programmer showing the original source code.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] In the 1960s, notably for ALGOL, whitespace and comments were eliminated as part of the line reconstruction phase (the initial phase of the compiler frontend), but this separate phase has been eliminated and these are now handled by the lexer.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The first stage, the *scanner*, is usually based on a finite-state machine (FSM).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] It has encoded within it information on the possible sequences of characters that can be contained within any of the tokens it handles (individual instances of these character sequences are termed lexemes).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] For example, an *integer* lexeme may contain any sequence of numerical digit characters.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] In some languages, the lexeme creation rules are more complex and may involve backtracking over previously read characters.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] For example, in C, one 'L' character is not enough to distinguish between an identifier that begins with 'L' and a wide-character string literal.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] A lexeme, however, is only a string of characters known to be of a certain kind (e.g., a string literal, a sequence of letters).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The second stage of a lexical analyzer, the *evaluator*, goes over the characters of the lexeme to produce a *value* containing relevant information for the parser.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The lexeme's type combined with its value is what properly constitutes a *token*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The value in the token can be whatever is deemed necessary for the parser to interpret a token of that type.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The evaluator may also suppress a lexeme entirely, concealing it from the parser, which is useful for whitespace and comments.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] This is practical if the list of tokens is small, but lexers generated by automated tooling as part of a compiler-compiler toolchain are more practical for a larger number of potential tokens.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] These tools generally accept regular expressions that describe the tokens allowed in the input stream.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Each regular expression is associated with a production rule in the lexical grammar of the programming language that evaluates the lexemes matching the regular expression.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] These tools may generate source code that can be compiled and executed or construct a state transition table for a finite-state machine (which is plugged into template code for compiling and executing).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Regular expressions compactly represent patterns that the characters in lexemes might follow.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] For example, for an English-based language, an IDENTIFIER token might be any English alphabetic character or an underscore, followed by any number of instances of ASCII alphanumeric characters and/or underscores.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] This could be represented compactly by the string `[a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z_0-9]*`.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] This means "any character a-z, A-Z or _, followed by 0 or more of a-z, A-Z, _ or 0-9".
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] It takes a full parser to recognize such patterns in their full generality.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] A parser can push parentheses on a stack and then try to pop them off and see if the stack is empty at the end (see example in the *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* book).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Typically, lexical tokenization occurs at the word level.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] However, it is sometimes difficult to define what is meant by a "word".
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] In languages that use inter-word spaces (such as most that use the Latin alphabet, and most programming languages), this approach is fairly straightforward.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] However, even here there are many edge cases such as contractions, hyphenated words, emoticons, and larger constructs such as URIs (which for some purposes may count as single tokens).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] A classic example is "New York-based", which a naive tokenizer may break at the space even though the better break is (arguably) at the hyphen.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Tokenization is particularly difficult for languages written in scriptio continua, which exhibit no word boundaries, such as Ancient Greek, Chinese, or Thai.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Agglutinative languages, such as Korean, also make tokenization tasks complicated.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Some ways to address the more difficult problems include developing more complex heuristics, querying a table of common special cases, or fitting the tokens to a language model that identifies collocations in a later processing step.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexers are often generated by a *lexer generator*, analogous to parser generators, and such tools often come together.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The most established is lex, paired with the yacc parser generator, or rather some of their many reimplementations, like flex (often paired with GNU Bison).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] These generators are a form of domain-specific language, taking in a lexical specification – generally regular expressions with some markup – and emitting a lexer.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] These tools yield very fast development, which is very important in early development, both to get a working lexer and because a language specification may change often.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Further, they often provide advanced features, such as pre- and post-conditions which are hard to program by hand.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] However, an automatically generated lexer may lack flexibility, and thus may require some manual modification, or an all-manually written lexer.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexer performance is a concern, and optimizing is worthwhile, more so in stable languages where the lexer runs very often (such as C or HTML). lex/flex-generated lexers are reasonably fast, but improvements of two to three times are possible using more tuned generators.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Hand-written lexers are sometimes used, but modern lexer generators produce faster lexers than most hand-coded ones.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The lex/flex family of generators uses a table-driven approach which is much less efficient than the directly coded approach.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] With the latter approach the generator produces an engine that directly jumps to follow-up states via goto statements.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Tools like re2c have proven to produce engines that are between two and three times faster than flex produced engines.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] It is in general difficult to hand-write analyzers that perform better than engines generated by these latter tools.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexical analysis mainly segments the input stream of characters into tokens, simply grouping the characters into pieces and categorizing them.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] However, the lexing may be significantly more complex; most simply, lexers may omit tokens or insert added tokens.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Omitting tokens, notably whitespace and comments, is very common when these are not needed by the compiler.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Less commonly, added tokens may be inserted.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] This is done mainly to group tokens into statements, or statements into blocks, to simplify the parser.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Line continuation is a feature of some languages where a newline is normally a statement terminator.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Most often, ending a line with a backslash (immediately followed by a newline) results in the line being *continued* – the following line is *joined* to the prior line.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] This is generally done in the lexer: The backslash and newline are discarded, rather than the newline being tokenized.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Examples include bash, other shell scripts and Python.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Many languages use the semicolon as a statement terminator.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Most often this is mandatory, but in some languages the semicolon is optional in many contexts.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] This is mainly done at the lexer level, where the lexer outputs a semicolon into the token stream, despite one not being present in the input character stream, and is termed *semicolon insertion* or *automatic semicolon insertion*.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] In these cases, semicolons are part of the formal phrase grammar of the language, but may not be found in input text, as they can be inserted by the lexer.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Optional semicolons or other terminators or separators are also sometimes handled at the parser level, notably in the case of trailing commas or semicolons.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is a feature of BCPL and its distant descendant Go, though it is absent in B or C.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is present in JavaScript, though the rules are somewhat complex and much-criticized; to avoid bugs, some recommend always using semicolons, while others use initial semicolons, termed defensive semicolons, at the start of potentially ambiguous statements.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] The off-side rule (blocks determined by indenting) can be implemented in the lexer, as in Python, where increasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting an INDENT token and decreasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting one or more DEDENT tokens.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] These tokens correspond to the opening brace `{` and closing brace `}` in languages that use braces for blocks and means that the phrase grammar does not depend on whether braces or indenting are used.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] This requires that the lexer hold state, namely a stack of indent levels, and thus can detect changes in indenting when this changes, and thus the lexical grammar is not context-free: INDENT–DEDENT depend on the contextual information of prior indent levels.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Generally lexical grammars are context-free, or almost so, and thus require no looking back or ahead, or backtracking, which allows a simple, clean, and efficient implementation.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] This also allows simple one-way communication from lexer to parser, without needing any information flowing back to the lexer.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] These examples all only require lexical context, and while they complicate a lexer somewhat, they are invisible to the parser and later phases.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] A more complex example is the lexer hack in C, where the token class of a sequence of characters cannot be determined until the semantic analysis phase since typedef names and variable names are lexically identical but constitute different token classes.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] Thus in the hack, the lexer calls the semantic analyzer (say, symbol table) and checks if the sequence requires a typedef name.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/lexical-analysis] In this case, information must flow back not from the parser only, but from the semantic analyzer back to the lexer, which complicates design.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Major processing tasks in an NLP system include: speech recognition, text classification, natural language understanding, and natural language generation.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Natural language processing has its roots in the 1950s.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Already in 1950, Alan Turing published an article titled "Computing Machinery and Intelligence," which proposed what is now called the Turing test as a criterion of intelligence, though at the time that was not articulated as a problem separate from artificial intelligence.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] The proposed test includes a task that involves the automated interpretation and generation of natural language.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Up until the 1980s, most natural language processing systems were based on complex sets of hand-written rules.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Starting in the late 1980s, however, there was a revolution in natural language processing with the introduction of machine learning algorithms for language processing.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Symbolic approach, i.e., the hand-coding of a set of rules for manipulating symbols, coupled with a dictionary lookup, was historically the first approach used both by AI in general and by NLP in particular: such as by writing grammars or devising heuristic rules for stemming.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] In the late 1980s and mid-1990s, the statistical approach ended a period of AI winter, which was caused by the inefficiencies of the rule-based approaches.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] The earliest decision trees, producing systems of hard if–then rules, were still very similar to the old rule-based approaches.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Only the introduction of hidden Markov models, applied to part-of-speech tagging, announced the end of the old rule-based approach.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] A major drawback of statistical methods is that they require elaborate feature engineering.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Since 2015, neural network–based methods have increasingly replaced traditional statistical approaches, using semantic networks and word embeddings to capture semantic properties of words.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Intermediate tasks (e.g., part-of-speech tagging and dependency parsing) are not needed anymore.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Neural machine translation, based on the then-newly invented sequence-to-sequence transformations, made obsolete the intermediate steps, such as word alignment, previously necessary for statistical machine translation.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] The following is a list of some of the most commonly researched tasks in natural language processing.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Some of these tasks have direct real-world applications, while others more commonly serve as subtasks that are used to aid in solving larger tasks.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Though natural language processing tasks are closely intertwined, they can be subdivided into categories for convenience.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given an image representing printed text, determine the corresponding text.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a sound clip of a person or people speaking, determine the textual representation of the speech.
