[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Indian language, however, such an approach is not possible, as each dictionary entry has thousands of possible word forms.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Many words, especially common ones, can serve as multiple parts of speech.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] ; and "out" can be any of at least five different parts of speech.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] The process of reducing inflected (or sometimes derived) words to a base form (e.g., "close" will be the root for "closed", "closing", "close", "closer" etc.).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Stemming yields similar results as lemmatization, but does so on grounds of rules, not a dictionary.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a chunk of text, find the sentence boundaries.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] (grammatical analysis) of a given sentence.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] and typical sentences have multiple possible analyses: perhaps surprisingly, for a typical sentence there may be thousands of potential parses (most of which will seem completely nonsensical to a human).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] What is the computational meaning of individual words in context?
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] How can we learn semantic representations from data?
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a stream of text, determine which items in the text map to proper names, such as people or places, and what the type of each such name is (e.g. person, location, organization).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] , and in any case, is often inaccurate or insufficient.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] For example, the first letter of a sentence is also capitalized, and named entities often span several words, only some of which are capitalized.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Furthermore, many other languages in non-Western scripts (e.g.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] ) do not have any capitalization at all, and even languages with capitalization may not consistently use it to distinguish names.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] This task is also referred to as token classification.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Sentiment analysis involves identifying and classifying the emotional tone expressed in text.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] This technique involves analyzing text to determine whether the expressed sentiment is positive, negative, or neutral.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] models designed to recognize both long-term and short-term dependencies in text sequences.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] The applications of sentiment analysis are diverse, extending to tasks such as categorizing customer reviews on various online platforms.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] The goal of terminology extraction is to automatically extract relevant terms from a given corpus.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] ; we have to select the meaning which makes the most sense in context.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] ; here we have to select the entity (a famous individual, a location, a company, etc.) which is referred to in context.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a chunk of text, identify the relationships among named entities (e.g. who is married to whom).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a sentence or larger chunk of text, determine which words ("mentions") refer to the same objects ("entities").
