[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] A Document AI platform sits on top of the NLP technology enabling users with no prior experience of artificial intelligence, machine learning or NLP to quickly train a computer to extract the specific data they need from different document types.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] NLP-powered Document AI enables non-technical teams to quickly access information hidden in documents, for example, lawyers, business analysts and accountants.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Computer systems intended to converse with a human.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a human-language question, determine its answer.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Typical questions have a specific right answer (such as "What is the capital of Canada?"), but sometimes open-ended questions are also considered (such as "What is the meaning of life?").
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a description of an image, generate an image that matches the description.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a description of a video, generate a video that matches the description.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Based on long-standing trends in the field, it is possible to extrapolate future directions of NLP.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Most higher-level NLP applications involve aspects that emulate intelligent behavior and apparent comprehension of natural language.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] More broadly speaking, the technical operationalization of increasingly advanced aspects of cognitive behavior represents one of the developmental trajectories of NLP(see trends among CoNLL shared tasks above).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Cognition refers to "the mental action or process of acquiring knowledge and understanding through thought, experience, and the senses." Cognitive science is the interdisciplinary, scientific study of the mind and its processes.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Cognitive linguistics is an interdisciplinary branch of linguistics, combining knowledge and research from both psychology and linguistics.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Especially during the age of symbolic NLP, the area of computational linguistics maintained strong ties with cognitive studies.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Assign relative measures of meaning to a word, phrase, sentence or piece of text based on the information presented before and after the piece of text being analyzed, e.g., by means of a probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] Ties with cognitive linguistics are part of the historical heritage of NLP, but they have been less frequently addressed since the statistical turn during the 1990s.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/natural-language-processing] More recently, ideas of cognitive NLP have been revived as an approach to achieve explainability, e.g., under the notion of "cognitive AI".
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The term has slightly different meanings in different branches of linguistics and computer science.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Traditional sentence parsing is often performed as a method of understanding the exact meaning of a sentence or word, sometimes with the aid of devices such as sentence diagrams.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] It usually emphasizes the importance of grammatical divisions such as subject and predicate.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Within computational linguistics the term is used to refer to the formal analysis by a computer of a sentence or other string of words into its constituents, resulting in a parse tree showing their syntactic relation to each other, which may also contain semantic information.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Some parsing algorithms generate a *parse forest* or list of parse trees from a string that is syntactically ambiguous.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The term is also used in psycholinguistics when describing language comprehension.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Within computer science, the term is used in the analysis of computer languages, referring to the syntactic analysis of the input code into its component parts in order to facilitate the writing of compilers and interpreters.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The term may also be used to describe a split or separation.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] In data analysis, the term is often used to refer to a process extracting desired information from data, e.g., creating a time series signal from a XML document.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The traditional grammatical exercise of parsing, sometimes known as *clause analysis*, involves breaking down a text into its component parts of speech with an explanation of the form, function, and syntactic relationship of each part.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] This is determined in large part from study of the language's conjugations and declensions, which can be quite intricate for heavily inflected languages.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] To parse a phrase such as "man bites dog" involves noting that the singular noun "man" is the subject of the sentence, the verb "bites" is the third person singular of the present tense of the verb "to bite", and the singular noun "dog" is the object of the sentence.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Techniques such as sentence diagrams are sometimes used to indicate relation between elements in the sentence.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Parsing was formerly central to the teaching of grammar throughout the English-speaking world, and widely regarded as basic to the use and understanding of written language.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] In some machine translation and natural language processing systems, written texts in human languages are parsed by computer programs.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Human sentences are not easily parsed by programs, as there is substantial ambiguity in the structure of human language, whose usage is to convey meaning (or semantics) amongst a potentially unlimited range of possibilities, but only some of which are germane to the particular case.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] So an utterance "Man bites dog" versus "Dog bites man" is definite on one detail but in another language might appear as "Man dog bites" with a reliance on the larger context to distinguish between those two possibilities, if indeed that difference was of concern.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] It is difficult to prepare formal rules to describe informal behaviour even though it is clear that some rules are being followed.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] In order to parse natural language data, researchers must first agree on the grammar to be used.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The choice of syntax is affected by both linguistic and computational concerns; for instance some parsing systems use lexical functional grammar, but in general, parsing for grammars of this type is known to be NP-complete.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Head-driven phrase structure grammar is another linguistic formalism which has been popular in the parsing community, but other research efforts have focused on less complex formalisms such as the one used in the Penn Treebank.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Shallow parsing aims to find only the boundaries of major constituents such as noun phrases.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Another popular strategy for avoiding linguistic controversy is dependency grammar parsing.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Most modern parsers are at least partly statistical; that is, they rely on a corpus of training data which has already been annotated (parsed by hand).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] This approach allows the system to gather information about the frequency with which various constructions occur in specific contexts.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] *(See machine learning.)* Approaches which have been used include straightforward PCFGs (probabilistic context-free grammars), maximum entropy, and neural nets.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Most of the more successful systems use *lexical* statistics (that is, they consider the identities of the words involved, as well as their part of speech).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] However such systems are vulnerable to overfitting and require some kind of smoothing to be effective.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Parsing algorithms for natural language cannot rely on the grammar having 'nice' properties as with manually designed grammars for programming languages.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] As mentioned earlier some grammar formalisms are very difficult to parse computationally; in general, even if the desired structure is not context-free, some kind of context-free approximation to the grammar is used to perform a first pass.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Algorithms which use context-free grammars often rely on some variant of the CYK algorithm, usually with some heuristic to prune away unlikely analyses to save time.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] *(See chart parsing.)* However some systems trade speed for accuracy using, e.g., linear-time versions of the shift-reduce algorithm.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] A somewhat recent development has been parse reranking in which the parser proposes some large number of analyses, and a more complex system selects the best option.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] In natural language understanding applications, semantic parsers convert the text into a representation of its meaning.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] In psycholinguistics, parsing involves not just the assignment of words to categories (formation of ontological insights), but the evaluation of the meaning of a sentence according to the rules of syntax drawn by inferences made from each word in the sentence (known as connotation).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] This normally occurs as words are being heard or read.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Neurolinguistics generally understands parsing to be a function of working memory, meaning that parsing is used to keep several parts of one sentence at play in the mind at one time, all readily accessible to be analyzed as needed.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Because the human working memory has limitations, so does the function of sentence parsing.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] This is evidenced by several different types of syntactically complex sentences that demonstrate potential issues for mental parsing of sentences.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The first, and perhaps most well-known, type of sentence that challenges parsing ability is the garden-path sentence.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] These sentences are designed so that the most common interpretation of the sentence appears grammatically faulty, but upon further inspection, these sentences are grammatically sound.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Garden-path sentences are difficult to parse because they contain a phrase or a word with more than one meaning, often their most typical meaning being a different part of speech.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] For example, in the sentence, "the horse raced past the barn fell", raced is initially interpreted as a past tense verb, but in this sentence, it functions as part of an adjective phrase.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Since parsing is used to identify parts of speech, these sentences challenge the parsing ability of the reader.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Another type of sentence that is difficult to parse is an attachment ambiguity, which includes a phrase that could potentially modify different parts of a sentence, and therefore presents a challenge in identifying syntactic relationship (i.e.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] A third type of sentence that challenges parsing ability is center embedding, in which phrases are placed in the center of other similarly formed phrases (i.e.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] "The rat the cat the man hit chased ran into the trap".) Sentences with 2 or in the most extreme cases 3 center embeddings are challenging for mental parsing, again because of ambiguity of syntactic relationship.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Within neurolinguistics there are multiple theories that aim to describe how parsing takes place in the brain.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The opposing, more contemporary model theorizes that within the mind, the processing of a sentence is not modular, or happening in strict sequence.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Rather, it poses that several different syntactic possibilities can be considered at the same time, because lexical access, syntactic processing, and determination of meaning occur in parallel in the brain.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] In this way these processes are integrated.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Although there is still much to learn about the neurology of parsing, studies have shown evidence that several areas of the brain might play a role in parsing.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] These include the left anterior temporal pole, the left inferior frontal gyrus, the left superior temporal gyrus, the left superior frontal gyrus, the right posterior cingulate cortex, and the left angular gyrus.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Although it has not been absolutely proven, it has been suggested that these different structures might favor either phrase-structure parsing or dependency-structure parsing, meaning different types of parsing could be processed in different ways which have yet to be understood.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Discourse analysis examines ways to analyze language use and semiotic events.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Persuasive language may be called rhetoric.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] A **parser** is a software component that takes input data (typically text) and builds a data structure – often some kind of parse tree, abstract syntax tree or other hierarchical structure, giving a structural representation of the input while checking for correct syntax.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The parsing may be preceded or followed by other steps, or these may be combined into a single step.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The parser is often preceded by a separate lexical analyser, which creates tokens from the sequence of input characters; alternatively, these can be combined in scannerless parsing.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Parsers may be programmed by hand or may be automatically or semi-automatically generated by a parser generator.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Parsing is complementary to templating, which produces formatted *output.* These may be applied to different domains, but often appear together, such as the scanf/printf pair, or the input (front end parsing) and output (back end code generation) stages of a compiler.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The input to a parser is typically text in some computer language, but may also be text in a natural language or less structured textual data, in which case generally only certain parts of the text are extracted, rather than a parse tree being constructed.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Parsers range from very simple functions such as scanf, to complex programs such as the frontend of a C++ compiler or the HTML parser of a web browser.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] An important class of simple parsing is done using regular expressions, in which a group of regular expressions defines a regular language and a regular expression engine automatically generating a parser for that language, allowing pattern matching and extraction of text.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] In other contexts regular expressions are instead used prior to parsing, as the lexing step whose output is then used by the parser.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] In the case of data languages, a parser is often found as the file reading facility of a program, such as reading in HTML or XML text; these examples are markup languages.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] In the case of programming languages, a parser is a component of a compiler or interpreter, which parses the source code of a computer programming language to create some form of internal representation; the parser is a key step in the compiler frontend.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Programming languages tend to be specified in terms of a deterministic context-free grammar because fast and efficient parsers can be written for them.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] For compilers, the parsing itself can be done in one pass or multiple passes – see one-pass compiler and multi-pass compiler.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The implied disadvantages of a one-pass compiler can largely be overcome by adding fix-ups, where provision is made for code relocation during the forward pass, and the fix-ups are applied backwards when the current program segment has been recognized as having been completed.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] An example where such a fix-up mechanism would be useful would be a forward GOTO statement, where the target of the GOTO is unknown until the program segment is completed.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] In this case, the application of the fix-up would be delayed until the target of the GOTO was recognized.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Conversely, a backward GOTO does not require a fix-up, as the location will already be known.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Context-free grammars are limited in the extent to which they can express all of the requirements of a language.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Informally, the reason is that the memory of such a language is limited.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The grammar cannot remember the presence of a construct over an arbitrarily long input; this is necessary for a language in which, for example, a name must be declared before it may be referenced.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] More powerful grammars that can express this constraint, however, cannot be parsed efficiently.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Thus, it is a common strategy to create a relaxed parser for a context-free grammar which accepts a superset of the desired language constructs (that is, it accepts some invalid constructs); later, the unwanted constructs can be filtered out at the semantic analysis (contextual analysis) step.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The following example demonstrates the common case of parsing a computer language with two levels of grammar: lexical and syntactic.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The first stage is the token generation, or lexical analysis, by which the input character stream is split into meaningful symbols defined by a grammar of regular expressions.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] For example, a calculator program would look at an input such as "`12 * (3 + 4)^2`" and split it into the tokens `12`, `*`, `(`, `3`, `+`, `4`, `)`, `^`, `2`, each of which is a meaningful symbol in the context of an arithmetic expression.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The lexer would contain rules to tell it that the characters `*`, `+`, `^`, `(` and `)` mark the start of a new token, so meaningless tokens like "`12*`" or "`(3`" will not be generated.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The next stage is parsing or syntactic analysis, which is checking that the tokens form an allowable expression.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] This is usually done with reference to a context-free grammar which recursively defines components that can make up an expression and the order in which they must appear.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] However, not all rules defining programming languages can be expressed by context-free grammars alone, for example type validity and proper declaration of identifiers.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] These rules can be formally expressed with attribute grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The final phase is semantic parsing or analysis, which is working out the implications of the expression just validated and taking the appropriate action.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] In the case of a calculator or interpreter, the action is to evaluate the expression or program; a compiler, on the other hand, would generate some kind of code.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Attribute grammars can also be used to define these actions.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The *task* of the parser is essentially to determine if and how the input can be derived from the start symbol of the grammar.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] by expanding all alternative right-hand-sides of grammar rules.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] This is known as the primordial soup approach.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Very similar to sentence diagramming, primordial soup breaks down the constituencies of sentences.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] A parser can start with the input and attempt to rewrite it to the start symbol.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Intuitively, the parser attempts to locate the most basic elements, then the elements containing these, and so on.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] LL parsers and recursive-descent parser are examples of top-down parsers that cannot accommodate left recursive production rules.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Their algorithm is able to produce both left-most and right-most derivations of an input with regard to a given context-free grammar.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] An important distinction with regard to parsers is whether a parser generates a *leftmost derivation* or a *rightmost derivation* (see context-free grammar).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] LL parsers will generate a leftmost derivation and LR parsers will generate a rightmost derivation (although usually in reverse).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Some *graphical parsing* algorithms have been designed for visual programming languages.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Parsers for visual languages are sometimes based on graph grammars.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Adaptive parsing algorithms have been used to construct "self-extending" natural language user interfaces.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] A simple parser implementation reads the entire input file, performs an intermediate computation or translation, and then writes the entire output file, such as in-memory multi-pass compilers.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Lookahead establishes the maximum incoming tokens that a parser can use to decide which rule it should use.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Lookahead is especially relevant to LL, LR, and LALR parsers, where it is often explicitly indicated by affixing the lookahead to the algorithm name in parentheses, such as LALR(1).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Most programming languages, the primary target of parsers, are carefully defined in such a way that a parser with limited lookahead, typically one, can parse them, because parsers with limited lookahead are often more efficient.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] One important change to this trend came in 1990 when Terence Parr created ANTLR for his Ph.D. thesis, a parser generator for efficient LL(*k*) parsers, where *k* is any fixed value.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] LR parsers typically have only a few actions after seeing each token.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] They are shift (add this token to the stack for later reduction), reduce (pop tokens from the stack and form a syntactic construct), end, error (no known rule applies) or conflict (does not know whether to shift or reduce).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Most programming languages (except for a few such as APL and Smalltalk) and algebraic formulas give higher precedence to multiplication than addition, in which case the correct interpretation of the example above is 1 + (2 * 3).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Note that Rule4 above is a semantic rule.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] It is possible to rewrite the grammar to incorporate this into the syntax.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] However, not all such rules can be translated into syntax.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Reduces "1" to expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Shift "+" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule1).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Shift "2" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule3).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Reduce stack element "2" to Expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Reduce stack items [E, +, E] and new input "E" to "E" based on rule1.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Shift "*" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule2).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Shift "3" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule3).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Reduce stack element "3" to expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Reduce stack items [E, *, E] and new input "E" to "E" based on rule2.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The parse tree and resulting code from it is not correct according to language semantics.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Reduce stack item 1 to simple Expression on input + based on rule3.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The lookahead is +, so we are on path to E +, so we can reduce the stack to E.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Shift + onto stack on input + in anticipation of rule1.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Shift 2 onto stack on input 2 in anticipation of rule3.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Reduce stack item 2 to Expression on input * based on rule3.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The lookahead * expects only E before it.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Now stack has E + E and still the input is *.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] It has two choices now, either to shift based on rule2 or reduction based on rule1.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Since * has higher precedence than + based on rule4, we shift * onto stack in anticipation of rule2.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Shift 3 onto stack on input 3 in anticipation of rule3.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Reduce stack item 3 to Expression after seeing end of input based on rule3.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Reduce stack items E * E to E based on rule2.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] Reduce stack items E + E to E based on rule1.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] The parse tree generated is correct and simply more efficient than non-lookahead parsers.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/parsing] This is the strategy followed in LALR parsers.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In corpus linguistics, **part-of-speech tagging** (**POS tagging**, **PoS tagging**, or **POST**), also called **grammatical tagging**, is the process of marking up a word in a text (corpus) as corresponding to a particular part of speech, based on both its definition and its context.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] A simplified form of this is commonly taught to school-age children, in the identification of words as nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs, etc.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Once performed by hand, POS tagging is now done in the context of computational linguistics, using algorithms which associate discrete terms, as well as hidden parts of speech, by a set of descriptive tags.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] POS-tagging algorithms fall into two distinctive groups: rule-based and stochastic.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Brill's tagger, one of the first and most widely used English POS taggers, employs rule-based algorithms.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Part-of-speech tagging is harder than just having a list of words and their parts of speech, because some words can represent more than one part of speech at different times, and because some parts of speech are complex.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] This is not rare—in natural languages (as opposed to many artificial languages), a large percentage of word-forms are ambiguous.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Correct grammatical tagging will reflect that "dogs" is here used as a verb, not as the more common plural noun.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Schools commonly teach that there are 9 parts of speech in English: noun, verb, article, adjective, preposition, pronoun, adverb, conjunction, and interjection.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] However, there are clearly many more categories and sub-categories.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For nouns, the plural, possessive, and singular forms can be distinguished.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In many languages words are also marked for their "case" (role as subject, object, etc.), grammatical gender, and so on; while verbs are marked for tense, aspect, and other things.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In some tagging systems, different inflections of the same root word will get different parts of speech, resulting in a large number of tags.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, NN for singular common nouns, NNS for plural common nouns, NP for singular proper nouns (see the POS tags used in the Brown Corpus).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Other tagging systems use a smaller number of tags and ignore fine differences or model them as features somewhat independent from part-of-speech.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In part-of-speech tagging by computer, it is typical to distinguish from 50 to 150 separate parts of speech for English.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Work on stochastic methods for tagging Koine Greek (DeRose 1990) has used over 1,000 parts of speech and found that about as many words were ambiguous in that language as in English.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] A morphosyntactic descriptor in the case of morphologically rich languages is commonly expressed using very short mnemonics, such as *Ncmsan* for Category = Noun, Type = common, Gender = masculine, Number = singular, Case = accusative, Animate = no.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The most popular "tag set" for POS tagging for American English is probably the Penn tag set, developed in the Penn Treebank project.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] It is largely similar to the earlier Brown Corpus and LOB Corpus tag sets, though much smaller.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In Europe, tag sets from the Eagles Guidelines see wide use and include versions for multiple languages.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] POS tagging work has been done in a variety of languages, and the set of POS tags used varies greatly with language.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Tags usually are designed to include overt morphological distinctions, although this leads to inconsistencies such as case-marking for pronouns but not nouns in English, and much larger cross-language differences.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The tag sets for heavily inflected languages such as Greek and Latin can be very large; tagging *words* in agglutinative languages such as Inuit languages may be virtually impossible.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] At the other extreme, Petrov et al. have proposed a "universal" tag set, with 12 categories (for example, no subtypes of nouns, verbs, punctuation, and so on).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Whether a very small set of very broad tags or a much larger set of more precise ones is preferable, depends on the purpose at hand.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Automatic tagging is easier on smaller tag-sets.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Research on part-of-speech tagging has been closely tied to corpus linguistics.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The first major corpus of English for computer analysis was the Brown Corpus developed at Brown University by Henry Kučera and W.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] It consists of about 1,000,000 words of running English prose text, made up of 500 samples from randomly chosen publications.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Each sample is 2,000 or more words (ending at the first sentence-end after 2,000 words, so that the corpus contains only complete sentences).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The Brown Corpus was painstakingly "tagged" with part-of-speech markers over many years.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] A first approximation was done with a program by Greene and Rubin, which consisted of a huge handmade list of what categories could co-occur at all.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, article then noun can occur, but article then verb (arguably) cannot.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Its results were repeatedly reviewed and corrected by hand, and later users sent in errata so that by the late 70s the tagging was nearly perfect (allowing for some cases on which even human speakers might not agree).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] This corpus has been used for innumerable studies of word-frequency and of part-of-speech and inspired the development of similar "tagged" corpora in many other languages.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Statistics derived by analyzing it formed the basis for most later part-of-speech tagging systems, such as CLAWS and VOLSUNGA.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] However, by this time (2005) it has been superseded by larger corpora such as the 100 million word British National Corpus, even though larger corpora are rarely so thoroughly curated.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For some time, part-of-speech tagging was considered an inseparable part of natural language processing, because there are certain cases where the correct part of speech cannot be decided without understanding the semantics or even the pragmatics of the context.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] This is extremely expensive, especially because analyzing the higher levels is much harder when multiple part-of-speech possibilities must be considered for each word.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In the mid-1980s, researchers in Europe began to use hidden Markov models (HMMs) to disambiguate parts of speech, when working to tag the Lancaster-Oslo-Bergen Corpus of British English.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] HMMs involve counting cases (such as from the Brown Corpus) and making a table of the probabilities of certain sequences.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, once you've seen an article such as 'the', perhaps the next word is a noun 40% of the time, an adjective 40%, and a number 20%.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Knowing this, a program can decide that "can" in "the can" is far more likely to be a noun than a verb or a modal.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The same method can, of course, be used to benefit from knowledge about the following words.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] More advanced ("higher-order") HMMs learn the probabilities not only of pairs but triples or even larger sequences.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] So, for example, if you've just seen a noun followed by a verb, the next item may be very likely a preposition, article, or noun, but much less likely another verb.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] When several ambiguous words occur together, the possibilities multiply.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] However, it is easy to enumerate every combination and to assign a relative probability to each one, by multiplying together the probabilities of each choice in turn.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The combination with the highest probability is then chosen.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The European group developed CLAWS, a tagging program that did exactly this and achieved accuracy in the 93–95% range.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] CLAWS pioneered the field of HMM-based part of speech tagging but was quite expensive since it enumerated all possibilities.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] It sometimes had to resort to backup methods when there were simply too many options (the Brown Corpus contains a case with 17 ambiguous words in a row, and there are words such as "still" that can represent as many as 7 distinct parts of speech.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] HMMs underlie the functioning of stochastic taggers and are used in various algorithms one of the most widely used being the bi-directional inference algorithm.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Church independently developed dynamic programming algorithms to solve the same problem in vastly less time.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Their methods were similar to the Viterbi algorithm known for some time in other fields.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] DeRose used a table of pairs, while Church used a table of triples and a method of estimating the values for triples that were rare or nonexistent in the Brown Corpus (an actual measurement of triple probabilities would require a much larger corpus).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Both methods achieved an accuracy of over 95%.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] DeRose's 1990 dissertation at Brown University included analyses of the specific error types, probabilities, and other related data, and replicated his work for Greek, where it proved similarly effective.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] These findings were surprisingly disruptive to the field of natural language processing.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The accuracy reported was higher than the typical accuracy of very sophisticated algorithms that integrated part of speech choice with many higher levels of linguistic analysis: syntax, morphology, semantics, and so on.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] CLAWS, DeRose's and Church's methods did fail for some of the known cases where semantics is required, but those proved negligibly rare.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] This convinced many in the field that part-of-speech tagging could usefully be separated from the other levels of processing; this, in turn, simplified the theory and practice of computerized language analysis and encouraged researchers to find ways to separate other pieces as well.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Markov Models became the standard method for the part-of-speech assignment.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The methods already discussed involve working from a pre-existing corpus to learn tag probabilities.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] It is, however, also possible to bootstrap using "unsupervised" tagging.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Unsupervised tagging techniques use an untagged corpus for their training data and produce the tagset by induction.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] That is, they observe patterns in word use, and derive part-of-speech categories themselves.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, statistics readily reveal that "the", "a", and "an" occur in similar contexts, while "eat" occurs in very different ones.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] With sufficient iteration, similarity classes of words emerge that are remarkably similar to those human linguists would expect; and the differences themselves sometimes suggest valuable new insights.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] These two categories can be further subdivided into rule-based, stochastic, and neural approaches.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Some current major algorithms for part-of-speech tagging include the Viterbi algorithm, Brill tagger, Constraint Grammar, and the Baum-Welch algorithm (also known as the forward-backward algorithm).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Hidden Markov model and visible Markov model taggers can both be implemented using the Viterbi algorithm.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The rule-based Brill tagger is unusual in that it learns a set of rule patterns, and then applies those patterns rather than optimizing a statistical quantity.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Many machine learning methods have also been applied to the problem of POS tagging.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Methods such as SVM, maximum entropy classifier, perceptron, and nearest-neighbor have all been tried, and most can achieve accuracy above 95%.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] A direct comparison of several methods is reported (with references) at the ACL Wiki.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] This comparison uses the Penn tag set on some of the Penn Treebank data, so the results are directly comparable.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] However, many significant taggers are not included (perhaps because of the labor involved in reconfiguring them for this particular dataset).
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Thus, it should not be assumed that the results reported here are the best that can be achieved with a given approach; nor even the best that *have* been achieved with a given approach.
[src:dependency-parsing-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In 2014, a paper reported using the structure regularization method for part-of-speech tagging, achieving 97.36% on a standard benchmark dataset.
